dentity and citizenship among both citizen and non-citizen residents and contribute to national imaginings of the future and a transnational Qatar. Looking beyond the branch campus, she also confronts mythologies of liberal and illiberal peoples, places, and ideologies that have developed around these universities. Supporters and detractors alike of branch campuses have long ignored the imperial histories of American universities and the exclusions and inequalities that continue to animate daily academic life. From the vantage point of Qatar, Teach for Arabia challenges the assumed mantle of liberalism in Western institutions and illuminates how people can contribute to decolonized university life and knowledge production.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aEducation, HigherxSocial aspectszQatar. 0aLiberalismzQatar. 0aSchools, AmericanzQatar. 0aTransnational educationxSocial aspectszQatar. 0aUniversities and collegeszQatar. 4aGulf Arab states. 4aMiddle East. 4aQatar. 4abranch campuses. 4acitizenship. 4aglobal education. 4ahigher education. 4aknowledge economy. 4aliberalism. 4asocial engineering. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Arabian Peninsula.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360751440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503607514423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503607514.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles